				<h1 class="section-header" id="goju-history-header">Brief History of GoJu-Ryu Karate Do</h1>

				<p id="goju-history-content" class="section-content">
					Okinawan Goju-ryu Karate is a distinctive fusion of Chinese Kung-fu and ancient Okinawan Te. Founded by Chojun Miyagi Sensei (1888-1953), this martial 
					art evolved from the teachings of his Sensei, Kanryo Higaonna Sensei (1853-1915), as Miyagi adjusted it to better suit the Okinawan people. Beyond self-defense, 
					Okinawan Goju-ryu Karate offers numerous health benefits through conditioning training and ancient breathing exercises.
					<br />
					<br />
					This style embraces sound biomechanical principles, harmonizing strong and subtle, hard and soft movements. The practice of Kata, a sequence of pre-arranged 
					movements, serves as a transformative process that hones both mind and body, shaping resilient and focused individuals.
					<br />
					<br />
					Ron Yamanaka Sensei, holding an 8th-degree black belt and the title of Kyoshi in Okinawan Goju-ryu Karate, directly studied under Ei’ichi Miyazato Sensei 
					(1922-1998), the top student of Chojun Miyagi Sensei. Yamanaka Sensei is a proud representative of authentic Okinawan Goju-ryu in Canada and holds the esteemed 
					title of Shibucho (head of family), bestowed upon him by Ei’ichi Miyazato Sensei.
					<br />
					<br />
					Embark on a journey through Okinawan Goju-ryu, where tradition and adaptation converge to shape the character of practitioners.
				</p>

